BEGIN_TEXT
Question 2:
$BR $SPACE $BR
Convert the exponential equation to the form \( Q = ae^{kt} \).  In the blanks, give the corresponding values for the values of $BITALIC a${EITALIC} and $BITALIC k${EITALIC} once you have rewritten the formula.  Give your answer for $BITALIC k${EITALIC} as the DECIMAL in your formula (not a percent) rounded to three decimal places.
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
\( Q = $a ($b)^t \) 
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( a = \) \{ ans_rule(10) \}
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( k = \) \{ ans_rule(10) \} 


END_TEXT

ANS( num_cmp($a) );
ANS( num_cmp($k,tol=>0.0006) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
To convert to the form \( Q=ae^{kt} \), we first say that the right sides of the two equations equal each other (since each equals $BITALIC Q${EITALIC}), and then we solve for $BITALIC a $EITALIC and $BITALIC k${EITALIC}.  Thus, we have \( ae^{kt} = $a($b)^t \).  At $BITALIC t $EITALIC = 0, we can solve for $BITALIC a $EITALIC: $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ ae^{k \cdot 0} = $a($b)^0 \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ a \cdot 1 =  $a \cdot 1 \)
$BR
Thus, we have \( $a e^{kt} = $a ($b)^t \), and we solve for \( k \): $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ $a e^{kt} = $a ($b)^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ e^{kt} = $b^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ \left( e^k \right)^t = ( $b )^t \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ e^k = $b \) $BR
\( \ \ \ \ \ \ k = \ln{ ($b) } \approx $k \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
Therefore, the equation is \( Q = $a e^{$k t} \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION
      
